Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The Department of Defense (DoD) Chief Information Officer (CIO) is focused on mobility within the Joint Information Environment (JIE) and has directed that information technology (IT) systems take advantage of technology and rapidly evolving devices to provide data to support the warfighter. During the Federal Government shutdown in October
2013, many users were unable to log onto the DCPDS system to request employment verification services. DCPDS requires a mobile access capability that would allow DoD civilians to perform authorized work from locations outside the office and to obtain information through non-GFE devices, while protecting DoD systems and associated PII data. DCPDS requires a DCPDS enterprise Identity and Access Management (IdAM) solution that integrates with the DISA single security architecture and their centralized IdAM DoD solution to protect PII data across the DoD.  To meet the security requirements and align with JIE initiatives, DCPDS also requires mobile device management and increased virtualization across the EHIRS enterprise. A more mobile use of DCPDS will better enable the usability of DCPDS and will transform how DoD operates, connects, and supports Federal Civilian employees in order to meet their mission objectives.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: Delivers production releases in accordance with the approved aquisition strategy.
PM Experience Level: 9 - No certification, but with less than two years PM experience (within the last five years)

Project Name: Upgrade of DCPDS Architecture and Application Enhancements
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Oracle announcement in March 2011 of the decision to discontinue all software development on the Intel Itanium processor has driven DCPDS to move to the Blade server architecture. This must be completed by January 2015.  Analysis is being performed, testing of configuration and performance, with orders placed for the replacement of all servers by mid-December 2014.  HR requirements need to be incorporated into DCPDS functionality to provide capabilities directly to employees and managers to meet the HR needs of customers.

Investment Title: INV - Messaging Services, Email and Remote Connectivity
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: This project is to upgrade world-wide to the latest version of the BlackBerry management suite - BlackBerry Enterprise Services 10 (formerly BlackBerry Mobile Fusion) and its next generation BlackBerry 10 handheld devices (already 140-2 FIPS certified).  This new system constitutes an architectural shift that should dramatically decrease the overall server footprint, improve BlackBerry performance at Posts with high latency, reduce impact to the Exchange environment, drastically improve system administration efficiency, avoid end of life issues, and provide the potential to support non-BlackBerry devices such as iPhones and Android devices. This project is no longer a pilot, it is full deployment. MRA will have to support both Blackberry 5 and Blackberry 10 infrastructure and work on transition users over to new system.  Also, provide new feature requests as they become available.  Introduce new devices as soon as they are available.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: Product version releases may occur more than twice a year frequent.
PM Experience Level: 5 - Other certification with between 2 and 4 years PM experience (within the last five years)

Investment Title: INV - Messaging Services, Email and Remote Connectivity
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The ClassNet Desktop Services Modernization Project (referred to as "ClassNet Modernization") is a Global Information Technology Modernization (GITM) sponsored project focusing on building, testing and deploying upgrades to the ClassNet terminal servers overseas, and ClassNet thin clients world-wide.  This project implement and deploy updates to the ClassNet Citrix servers overseas, overseas fat clients, and thin clients world-wide to align the ClassNet system with objectives identified in the DoS IT Strategic Plan (ITSP) for fiscal years 2011-2013.  It is (1) Building, testing and making available Windows Embedded Standard (WES) 7, WES 2009 and HP Zero Client operating system images to 6700 overseas and 6000 domestic thin clients currently using embedded XP (XPe) operating system (XPe reaches End-of-Life in January 12, 2016), (2) Updating physical terminal servers from Windows 2003 to the Windows 2008R2 operating system,  and upgrading server memory and drives, (3) Installing Citrix XenApp 6.5 on terminal servers to support enhanced client monitoring and port security, (4) Integrating the latest PKI hardware and software, (5) Standardizing the baseline image installed on physical and virtual terminal servers (establishing an SOE-S), (6) Standardizing the baseline image presented to all ClassNet end users, (7) Ensuring system assets are under centralized management and configuration control, (8) Designing the system to meet short-term and long-term resource requirements, and (9) Upgrading the overseas fat clients running on the XP OS to the Microsoft Windows 7 image.

Investment Title: INV - Messaging Services, Email and Remote Connectivity
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Citrix XenMobile Mobile Device Management solution allows for the comprehensive management of Government Furnished Equipment (GFE) mobile devices, apps and data.  It provides users access to approved mobile applications from a unified corporate apps store, including seamlessly-integrated email, browser, data sharing and supported apps.  IRM maintains control over mobile devices with full configuration, security, provisioning and support capabilities, ensuring compliance and control requirements while providing users with the freedom of a mobile device.  It will also serve as a launch bed to expand support of Department mobile applications on a secure platform. Leveraging the XenMobile platform on non-BlackBerry devices expands the Department's portfolio and limits its risk exposure to any potential business downgrade from BlackBerry.  Should that business falter, the Department would have a readily available alternate solution that will have been vetted and tested in the field. Introducing new mobile devices to start from Apple and then adding Android and Windows devices.

The GO 2.0 project is triggered by the department's requirement to expand telework program. Currently, the worldwide user base is currently over 25,000 customers:  GO provides a standard desktop image using Citrix XenApp and XenDesktop which allows for a streamlined remote access experience for the diplomat on-the-go. Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: CMS MACBIS (Medicaid & CHIP Business Information and Solutions)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
About MACPro: 
Medicaid, authorized by Title XIX of the Social Security Act, and CHIP, reauthorized by the Children's Health Insurance Program Reauthorization Act of 2009 (CHIPRA) signed into law on February 4, 2009, play an important role in financing health care for approximately 48 million people throughout the country. By 2014, it is expected that an additional 16 million people will become eligible for Medicaid and CHIP as a result of the Affordable Care Act (Public Law 111-148 - Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act). In order to implement the statute, CMS must provide for a mechanism to ensure timely approval of Medicaid and CHIP state plans, waivers and demonstrations and provide for a repository for all Medicaid and CHIP program that supplies data to populate Healthcare.gov (sec. 1103) as well as other required reports. With these tremendous statutory changes in the Medicaid and CHIP programs, CMS will undergo a transformation from a reactive, mostly paper based processing entity to an active, electronic based program manager by automating and streamlining the current systems and processes.

About T-MSIS:
The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) implemented the T-MSIS initiative in an effort to receive more complete and timely Medicaid and Children's Health Insurance Programs (CHIP) related data from states. This initiative seeks to reduce the burden on states of multiple requests for data, allowing states to better perform its responsibilities of Medicaid and CHIP program oversight, administration, and program integrity.
PM Experience Level: 4 - Other certification with 4 or more years PM experience (within the last five years)

The ALM initiative is designed to meet the authorities of the OCIO to reduce the overall spend on commoditized IT; make it easier for mission users to access sensitive, time-critical data; protect privacy, civil rights, and civil liberties and improve the security decision making of DHS authorization business processes. Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Continuous Diagnostics and Mitigation (CDM) program is a dynamic approach to fortifying the cybersecurity of government networks and systems.  CDM provides federal departments and agencies with capabilities and tools that identify cybersecurity risks on an ongoing basis, prioritize these risks based upon potential impacts, and enable cybersecurity personnel to mitigate the most significant problems first.  Congress established the CDM program to provide adequate, risk-based, and cost-effective cybersecurity and more efficiently allocate cybersecurity resources. (OMB M-14-03).

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The purpose of the Operational Security Assessment project is to analyze an agency’s information architecture and related processes to develop a threat profile for the agency’s IT security components, or its layers and sub-layers of security, as shown in Table 1. The security assessment will identify the nature of the threats and the likely vulnerabilities of the given piece of technology associated with an agency’s business. The security assessment will also examine and evaluate the agency’s operational security policies, procedures, and systems through the performance of technological reviews.  The expected outcome is:  provide technical reviews and recommendations that are aligned with current industry best practices for improving the overall security posture;the SAM’s assessment methods and procedures, findings, and recommendations can be used as evidence/artifacts by agencies to satisfy the reporting requirements for an ATO in USDA’s Annual Authorization process for the controls assessed by the security assessment; conduct security assessment of selected agencies and assess effectiveness of corrective actions by agencies to remediate vulnerabilities.
PM Experience Level: 4 - Other certification with 4 or more years PM experience (within the last five years)

This task will include a requirements gap analysis, development of design documents project management planning (to include project scheduling, quality management, requirements gathering, risk management), test planning, and transition-in planning (for contact center, warehouse, data, and inventory). This task shall also include the development of interface control documents with United States Mint's internal/external systems and finally build development/integration/test environment.

This task, as a minimum, shall include any necessary updates to the plans identified in the logical design phase, configuration and coding (if necessary), preparation of production environment(s), the execution of testing activities, integration, transition-in (to include data, inventory, contact center and warehouse), Contractor training, USM staff training, and deployment. The contractor shall deliver the functional and business operations needs identified in the Statement of Objectives Appendix A. At a minimum, the Contractor is responsible for the integration of its system to the following seven individual internal/external systems utilized by United Stated Mint. FIT recently completed a blueprint for financial management shared services.  The blueprint recommends a shared service approach whereby all Federal agencies migrate to one of several designated Federal and private financial management shared service providers (SSP) that offer, at a minimum, a common set of financial management services and products.  Further, the approach includes a lifecycle approval step where FIT reviews and compares an agency's migration proposal to the common services and products to verify the following:  (1) the agency's needs align with the common services and products; (2) the agency can offer support (e.g., regulatory, statutory) for any needs beyond the common services and products; and (3) any verified Services and Products gaps can be satisfied by one of the designated SSPs.  Once an agency has an acceptable modernization plan, it will begin a brief "discovery" phase with an SSP process whereby both organizations must agree that the services and products offered by the SSP satisfy the needs of the agency.

FIT has developed a series of financial management measures (e.g., price per invoice, on-time payments, discounts and interest paid) to capture the price and performance of a number of financial management processes (e.g., procure-to-pay, bill-to-collect) provided by Federal SSPs.  FIT captures and aggregates the measures reported by the SSPs in a reporting tool (or "benchmarking tool") that aggregates the information as a government-wide benchmark.  FIT, Federal SSPs, and Federal agencies can use the benchmarking tool to compare the cost and performance of the Federal agencies financial management activities to the price and performance of the Federal SSPs.  The benchmarking tool is a web-based application with defined metrics based on seven financial management end-to-end business processes, including Procure-to-Pay and Bill-to-Collect.  The metrics are based on the price and performance of the aligned business processes of the Federal SSPs.  Examples of the metrics include price per invoice, statement of differences, on- time payments, discounts and interest paid.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Sample Survey Operations support IES's mission to provide national leadership in expanding fundamental knowledge and understanding of education from early childhood through postsecondary study. A significant component of the Institute’s independent research activity relies upon data gathered via sample surveys; that is, surveys (or assessments) of a scientifically-selected sample comprised of individual students or schools from the population of interest. The Sample Survey Operations project includes pre-production, production, and post-production activities that subsume tasks related to (a) sampling and instrumentation development; (b) tracing, locating, and interviewing; and (c) editing, weighting, imputation, and data file development, respectively.

Dissemination Operations support IES's mission to provide parents, educators, students, researchers, policymakers, and the general public with reliable information about the condition and progress of education in the United States, including early childhood education; educational practices that support learning and improve academic achievement and access to educational opportunities for all students; and the effectiveness of Federal and other education programs. The Dissemination Operations project includes activities that subsume tasks related to (a) needs analysis, requirements development, and analysis of alternatives for a wide range of dissemination options ranging from web-based tools to online publications; (b) development, technical review, and release of dissemination products; and (c) dissemination product maintenance.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) Trusted Internet Connections (TIC) Project was formed to comply with Office Management and Budget (OMB) Memorandum M-08-05, "Implementation of Trusted Internet Connections".  The purpose of the TIC program is to optimize individual external connections, including Internet Points of Presence (PoP) currently in use by the federal government.  The TIC Initiative establishes a basis for consolidated infrastructure to achieve interoperability and communication among operating divisions.  In response to this initiative, HHS will adopt a network and security architecture that complies with the Department of Homeland Security (DHS) TIC requirements and reduces the total number of external connections to include Internet, inter-agency, partner, contractor, educational, health and research connectivity.   Once implemented, the TIC environment will improve HHS's incident response capability; reduce the number of external connection points within HHS; and provide centralized monitoring of HHS network security controls.  HHS TIC aligns with the HHS 2007-2012 Strategic Plan for IT infrastructure consolidation.  This strategy employs the sharing and reuse of common, standards-based materials and programs that support the business of computer technology.
SDLC Methodology: 7 - Not Primarily a Software Development Project
Release Every Six Mo Comment: The project is not software development.  The TIC Initiative establishes a basis for consolidated infrastructure to achieve interoperability and communication among operating divisions.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Distribution Standard System (DSS) is a fully deployed contemporary system in sustainment since 1999. The DSS is a key component of Defense Logistics Agency's (DLA's) Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) architecture with DLA''s ERP tool, the Enterprise Business System (EBS).  The DSS provides effective and efficient worldwide support to Warfighters and other federal and civilian customers, supporting the automation of large, complex, and critical distribution functions.  And, through its integration with the ERP based components and interfaces with other military service systems, DSS completes the Department of Defense (DoD) end-to end supply chain. DSS directly supports the management of wholesale and retail distribution for DOD inventory control points, Service maintenance depots, civil emergencies, and foreign military sales. The DSS component controls the storage, allocation, and movement of Air Force, Navy, Army, Marine, and DLA inventories.  In order to continually support the changing customer base and requirements, System Change Requests (SCRs) are accomplished annually to the DSS software.

Project Name:
H12121
PREDICT: Pattern Representation and Evaluation of Data through Integration, Correlation, and Transformation
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The hypothesis of this proposed effort is to demonstrate that reducing clinician cognitive load by consolidating complex multimodal physiological information into coherent images using data visualization will result in reductions in medical error and improvements in patient care, safety, and efficiency. The research objective is to design, develop, and test a prototype data visualization system that (1) integrates and presents complex disparate data streams into dynamic visualizations that enable clinicians to more easily assimilate the information and derive insight from it, and (2) provides interactive tools that align cognitive perceptions and understanding among members of the clinical team resulting in faster more accurate treatment decisions. Furthermore, we propose to empirically evaluate our interface design by conducting an experiment testing our interface to the current one by presenting cases to clinicians using historical patient data collected from the NICU.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
Interactions between medicine and industry have a wide spectrum of purposes and resulting impacts. Collaboration may promote discovery and development of new technologies that improve individual and public health. However, financial ties may create conflicts of interest in other aspects of medicine: clinical practice, clinical and basic science research, medical education, standard setting, and medical publications.
Applicable manufacturers and group purchasing organizations (GPOs) must begin collection of all applicable transfers of value starting on August 1, 2013 and must report the data to CMS and attest to the data on an annual basis thereafter. After a formal data review and dispute process by the covered recipients and submission of corrections by the applicable manufacturers and GPOs, CMS must publish the data on a public website. Data must be published in a way that it is easy to use, is searchable, can be aggregated, and is downloadable.
Manufacturers who produce any drugs, devices, biologicals, or medical supplies covered under Medicare, Medicaid, or the Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP) are subject to Open Payments reporting requirements. Except in special circumstances outlined in the Final Rule, applicable manufacturers and GPOs must disclose and attest to all applicable transactions (payments, other transfers of value, investment interests, etc.) made to any covered recipients, regardless of whether the transfer of value was related to a covered product.
CMS anticipates that patients, physicians, manufacturers, GPOs, third party commercial services, the press, academic researchers, other researchers, and the general public will utilize the data collected by this program.
PM Experience Level: 4 - Other certification with 4 or more years PM experience (within the last five years)

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The purpose of this project is to collect, edit, and store encounter data submitted by Medicare Medicaid Plans (MMPs) and other entities' encounter data necessary to describe and price (Medicare only) a health care encounter along with any other activity as directed under the Capitated Financial Alignment Demonstration. 
Under the capitated model of the financial alignment demonstrations, the Medicare-Medicaid Coordination Office is working with participating States to test a new payment and service delivery model to improve the quality of care that individuals dually eligible for Medicare and Medicaid (Medicare-Medicaid enrollees) receive.  The goals are to expand access to seamless, integrated programs, while reducing expenditures under Medicare and Medicaid, and enhancing the quality of care furnished. 
This project modifies the existing Encounter Data System (EDS) for purposes of processing those encounter data described as being Medicare services to develop the capability to price the MMP health care encounter data to be able to estimate the cost of a dually eligible beneficiary enrolled in an MMP. For those encounter data described as being Medicaid services, the data is collected, edited at the translator level and stored along with the Medicare services encounter data in the CMS Repository. Under this project a copy of all encounter data submitted by the MMPs is also sent to the corresponding State Medicaid Agency. The project includes analysis, development, testing, implementation, and maintenance of the Medicare Medicaid Data System (MMDS), including modifications to EDS, as well as operational and policy training to MMPs and other entities. Inherent existing functionality of the EDS, such as identification of diagnoses codes to be sent to the Risk Adjustment Processing System (RAPS), processing and submitting Part D Events is included.
Because the system is modified to receive Demonstration Medicaid Encounters as well, the capacity to process encounters submitted in the NCPDP format and Dental Encounters will be added.
PM Experience Level: 8 - No certification, but with between 2 and 4 years PM experience (within the last five years)

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The purpose of this effort is to develop 1) an algorithm or a set of business rules which, when transformed into a system solution, successfully disaggregates by payer (Medicare or Medicaid) one file containing integrated encounter data submitted  by Medicare-Medicaid Plans (MMP) as part of the Capitated Financial Alignment Demonstration, into two separate files. The separation of encounter data is to be determined using only the data submitted (claims based). The exception to this is Medicare Part D covered drugs, which are already submitted via a separate process as Medicare Prescription Drug Event (PDE) data.  The determination of and separation by payer for each submitted encounter is to occur, post-receipt, using a set of standard business rules which shall be established under this task.
 
An additional primary function of this effort is 2) to develop functionality which allows the participants of the Demonstration, both the plans as well as State partners, to  receive and transmit data files in different formats, either variations of existing EDI national standards (e.g. ASC X12 5010X 837) or custom formats.
 
If it has been determined that a successful algorithm has been built and CMS decides to move forward, a second, optional function of this task shall be to 3) operationalize the set of business rules into a service, i.e., an IT solution, which is either hosted or deployed and supported by a platform that is to be built by the contractor, upon determination of design. It is mandatory that the service or solution shall maintain the existing functionality between submitter and receiver (MMP to CMS front-end system) and shall maintain the exchange of transactional messages, reports and all other communication.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: Production releases will occur for each of the separate goals: 1) operationalization of business rules, 2) individual releases for each state's MMPs on an ongoing basis.
PM Experience Level: 5 - Other certification with between 2 and 4 years PM experience (within the last five years)

Project Name: FAN 2.0 Pilots and Proofs of Concept
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
In order to better serve the Department of State workforce and the Foreign Service community that utilizes the Department's resources, various technologies and enhancement will be deployed as proofs of concept to measure their impact and benefit to the community.  If beneficial, it is expected that these pilots and proofs of concept will lead to full-scale implementation; however if a proof of concept does not meet expectations, the Department can stop funding before a large investment is made.

Some primary initiatives include:

Virtual Desktop Infraastrructure (VDI): Separates the desktop environment and subsequent applications from the physical desktop client device to a centralized virtual server serving multiple users concurrently on zero-client or thin-client devices.

Wireless Network Infrastructure: State-provided wireless access (WiFi) will allow users in Department of State offices and meeting rooms to work together with more flexibility and mobility.  The expected outcome of implementing wireless network infrastructure is to provide wireless access throughout Department facilities.

Eligible Family Member(EFM): Enables EFM access to various Department of State services.
SDLC Methodology: 7 - Not Primarily a Software Development Project
Release Every Six Mo Comment: This project is not primary a software development project and as such would not have releases every 6 months.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Enable JSOC, DOJ components, and bureaus to conduct automated, advanced and dynamic analytics of cyber activity to determine if malware exists.  These next generation tools do not use static signature defined anti-virus which is ineffective against current threats.  Solution will be able to block malware that is found from executing on live DOJ networks.  DOJ requires a dedicated suite of capabilities to identify, prevent, and if necessary hunt, pursue, and mitigate Advanced Persistent Threats (APTs) that target DOJ networks.  These are high end threats that current capabilities (A/V, configuration, etc.) do not catch.  Currently DOJ can not inspect over 40% of network traffic because it is encrypted through SSL from host inside DOJ networks to destination; exactly where APT's operate.  Likewise, when APT are successful, DOJ can only maintain 5 days of PCAP information to rebuild network sessions and analyze the attack.  30-60 days is the industry standard to allow for notification and proper investigation of the malicious activity.  Implementing solutions will help position DOJ security services and defend the Department's networks and data.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: This is an integration project, not a software development project so a production release construct is not applicable.  Project will use traditional project management milestones.
PM Experience Level: 7 - No certification, but with 4 or more years PM experience (within the last five years)

These modules support agents and officers throughout the various workflow stages of their daily intelligence tracking, apprehension, and enforcement activities. The latter two modules are used by a sub-set of specialized units within the USBP and Office of Field Operations (OFO) to track and manage cases for enforcement programs. The purpose/objective of e3 is to provide a single-entry option for agents to report enforcement incidents, and to collect and process information for reporting measures on the mission, goals, and priorities established by DHS.

The Enterprise Geospatial Information System (eGIS) Program provides CBP personnel with enterprise level geospatial services. These services support personnel in allowing for the creation, searching and accessing of maps and geographic location datasets within a role based administration system. They include the eGIS Map Viewer, Universal Location Point Selector, Portal Application and REST/KML services. The program has expanded with the goal of providing services to other DHS component offices, such as ICE and USCG. The objective of eGIS is to provide situational awareness to all levels of CBP via geographic mapping systems with near real-time information necessary to secure our borders and support the CBP mission.

The ICAD system is the current U.S. Border Patrol command and control system supporting real-time border surveillance and monitoring of agent activity/officer safety. The system identifies and classifies intrusion events from surveillance resources including fielded sensors. The objective of ICAD is to 
collect real-time data on sensor status and activations, which indicate potential terrorist, smuggler or illegal alien movement, compile and relay necessary information to other IT systems and USBP personnel, and monitor and relay agent dispatch status and agent safety information.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: NASA/CSO currently operates two entirely separate backbone infrastructures; one for critical spacecraft and science operations, and one for Agency Corporate services. Three projects have been initiated with the goal to optimize these backbone infrastructures to reduce cost and improve service delivery. Of the three CSO projects (MngA , BB-ER, and MBT), MBT is the primary source of cost savings for the Agency. Additional business analysis is provided in Section 3.The Mission Next Generation Architecture (MngA) will implement the new Mission network architecture required to support emerging and upcoming mission concepts and requirements, using the CSO backbone infrastructure wherever possible to reduce overall cost of wide area Mission network services. Simultaneously, the Backbone Equipment Refresh (BB-ER) project will leverage a technology refresh to position the CSO Backbone to support these Mission Network needs. The Mission Backbone Transition (MBT) is the final phase of this process to optimize the CSO backbone infrastructure, with the goal to fully leverage the MngA and BB-ER products to maximize savings and service.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: Approach was waterfall, and requirements/development approach did not favor a six month release cycle

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The Hospital Quality Reporting System is a quality reporting program where participating hospitals provide CMS with data to help consumers make more informed decisions about their health care. The data is available at www.hospitalcompare.hhs.gov and www.data.medicare.gov. Through legislation, CMS is authorized to pay hospitals a higher annual update to their payment rates if they successfully report designated quality measures. The program began with the Inpatient Quality Reporting Program and now represents several health care provider types (no longer just "hospitals ).
 
The Hospital IQR Program was developed as a result of the Medicare Prescription Drug, Improvement and Modernization Act (MMA) of 2003. Section 5001(a) of Pub. 109-171 of the Deficit Reduction Act (DRA) of 2005 provided new requirements for the Hospital IQR Program, which built on the voluntary Hospital Quality Initiative.
 
The Hospital IQR Program requires "sub-section (d)" hospitals to submit data for specific quality measures for health conditions common among people with Medicare, and which typically result in hospitalization. If they successfully participate in the program, they are eligible to receive their full Medicare reimbursement (of which CMS withholds a percentage until they successfully meet the annual criteria).
PM Experience Level: 4 - Other certification with 4 or more years PM experience (within the last five years)

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: CMS has implemented quality measure reporting programs for multiple settings of care.These programs are intended to promote higher quality and more efficient health care of Medicare beneficiaries. The reporting of quality measures for ambulatory services is intended to encourage clinicians to improve their quality of care and to empower consumers with information to make more educated health care decisions.CMS is seeking to align payment for high quality of care across settings through the Physician Quality Reporting System (PQRS, the Medicare EHR Incentive Program (MU) and the Physician Value-Based Modifier (VBM) program. These payment adjustments are meant to synthesize CMS' efforts to improve the quality and value of health care delivered in the United States and to shift the Medicare fee for service program away from paying providers based solely on the volume of services and instead paying them for quality and value of care. CMS provides tools to providers that enable them to measure and monitor resource use and costs. Through the combination of quality metrics, resource utilization tools and cost information, the framework for the development of measures of efficiency have been established. Providers are rewarded for the delivery of high quality, low cost care and encouraged to compete on the basis of quality and cost.
PM Experience Level: 4 - Other certification with 4 or more years PM experience (within the last five years)

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The Center for Clinical Standards and Quality (CCSQ) leads the CMS Quality Reporting program, Value Based Purchasing program, and selected eServices.   The Information Systems Group (ISG) within CCSQ maintains the Heath Care Quality Information System (HCQIS) enterprise which supports these CCSQ quality programs and Lines of Business (LOBs).  ISG vision is to architect, build, and support innovative health care IT systems which focus on optimizing CCSQ clinical standards and quality programs.
The goal is to ensure that these common business functions are supported through a common architecture and system for submission of data, parsing, staging and processing the data to a common data framework that does not duplicate data stores, but allows for the proper business intelligence and measure calculations to be run against an integrated data framework. The framework and design should accommodate both the reporting and file outputs in the most efficient manner. The time required to make changes, should be minimal without requiring entire systems to be redeveloped, but only modular components. All business functions should be handled through the design and implementation of scalable enterprise services, and that perform to the expected load.
While the LOBs are moving forward with their business needs, Enterprise Services oversees all technical functional areas, assuring that the technology proposed within the Targeted Enterprise Architecture (TEA) is within the LOB's need.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: CMS Quality Improvement Organizations (QIO) Information Systems
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The Peer Review Improvement Act of 1982 (Title I, subtitle C of the Tax Equity and Fiscal Responsibility Act of 1982 (TEFRA), Pub. L. 97-248) amended Part B of title XI of the Social Security Act (the Act) by establishing the Utilization and Quality Control Peer Review Organization program, now known as the Quality Improvement Organizations (QIOs). The Health and Human Services department of the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services administers the QIO contracts.
QIOs work under contract on strategic initiatives and projects that seek to achieve CMS's aims of better health care, better health and lower healthcare costs through improvement for all Medicare beneficiaries. CMS anticipates their efforts will likely have a secondary effect of aiding in the transformation of the health care system. The QIO goals align with CMS's achievement of the National Quality Strategy (NQS) and the CMS Quality Strategy along with the other goals, recommendations, and priorities. QIOs review medical care, help beneficiaries with complaints about the quality of care, and implement improvements across the spectrum of care. Beginning with the 11th SoW in August 1, 2014, QIO contracts are 5 years in length and has two types of QIO contractors. Beneficiary and Family Centered Care QIOs and Quality Innovation Network QIOs. BFCC-QIOs perform medical review and QIN-QIOs develop and work with providers on quality improvement activities.
PM Experience Level: 7 - No certification, but with 4 or more years PM experience (within the last five years)

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: DLAs communications infrastructure is the base upon which all of DLA depends.  With 250+ operating locations, DLA users at all locations must be able to use networked computing devices (laptops, desktops, thin clients, etc..), land line phones, video teleconferencing equipment, and well as cell phones / DPA / smartphones where required.  The communications infrastructure expenditures fall into  five main areas:  1.  Building and maintaining  a capability for the DLA employees, 2.  Monitoring it for availability, 3.  Troubleshooting and repairing it when outages occur, 4.  Secureing it against threats, and 4.  Maintaining it through lifecycle refresh.  Item one includes the initial purchase of such items as Network switches/routers, network circuits, intrusion prevention and detection devices, firewalls, network sniffers, phones, VTC equipment, Satcomm equipment, and phones, in addition to support personnel to maintain the equipment through patching and researching patches required to maintain STIG compliance and accreditation of the equipment.  Item two includes software and hardware, plus personnel support  to monitor.  Item three requires specialized hardware and software be maintained in order to properly find and resolve issues.  Issues may take the form of network circuit degradation or complete outage, degradation or complete loss of service, hardware malfunction or failure.  Most outages take many man-hours to pinpoint, and then develop and implement a solution.  Item four also requires dedicated and specialized hardware, software, and personnel.  The hardware include Firewalls, intrusion detection devices for monitoring, proxy servers, reverse web proxy devices, and web content filtering devices.  Each of these items normally has proprietary hardware and software required to run the devices, and personnel trained and certified to manage them.  Item 5 - while seemingly the easiest to list is possibly the most extensive.  Nearly all Communications devices require a 5 year life cycle replacement. While there are exceptions (VoIP phones have 7 year expectations, and wiring normally has a 10 year life expectancy), all equipment must have a plan for replacement - to include the purchase of new equipment, planning for the install, and the support of personnel to physically carry out the replacement.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: FDA CTP Regulatory Compliance and Inspection
Project Name: FDA CTP RCI Case Management System (CCMS)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The objective of this project is to develop and implement an IT system which can be used to manage Tobacco Civil Money Penalty (CMP) and No-Tobacco-Sale Order (NTSO) cases that are brought before an ALJ.  The CCMS Application will be utilizing the Microsoft Dynamics CRM 2013 software.  OCE will be spearheading the development of the system on behalf of the CCMS.  FDA CCMS Application will function as a repository for all documents associated with cases brought by CTP against violating tobacco retailers.   The IT system will also function as a case tracking system for case management to be used by the ALJ to ensure statutorily mandated deadlines are met.  To support its compliance and enforcement activities, CCMS will allow close collaboration with ALJ.  On average, there are 10 or fewer documents for cases that quickly close without a hearing, and those cases are a majority of the cases reviewed by the ALJ.  Cases that require a hearing may have 50 or more documents associated with them.  In FY14, there were over 1000 CMP cases brought by CTP before the ALJ, and this number is expected to grow over time.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: Project is in development. There is no routine production rollout during this phase.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The End Stage Renal Disease Quality Reporting System (EQRS) is a consolidation of IT systems - CROWNWeb, REMIS, and ESRD QIP - that supports the Medicare End Stage Renal Disease (ESRD) Program. The ESRD Program is a national health insurance program for people with irreversible kidney failure. Established in 1972, this program led to the creation and maintenance by CMS of a comprehensive patient registry for the entire ESRD population in the United States. Maintaining this patient registry requires the submission of patient/clinical/provider data as well as the production of performance analyses on quality data for the CMS ESRD program. Each of the three systems - - CROWNWeb, REMIS, and ESRD QIP - support the registry, the ESRD program, and EQRS consolidation.
